    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="586"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d586">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 300.115/904</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_VDH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Van Dyke</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Hague</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-22">
                        <hi rend="italic">October 22, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 8 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>51. Answering your 44, 21st. Foreign Minister has just changed information given
                    me October 16 and conveyed in my 47:</p>
                <p>From to-day permits for consigning goods to Netherlands Government will not be
                    granted through Consul General, New York, but directly by Government here to the
                    Holland-America Line who will inform their agent at New York accordingly. Only
                    goods whose reexportation is forbidden can be so consigned. Naturally the
                    prohibition of export does not apply to goods In transit destined for
                    belligerent country; such goods, however, cannot be consigned to Netherlands
                    Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_VDH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Van Dyke</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
